Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Semiclassical Implementation", "TechNoteSection",
 CellID->1845626348,ExpressionUUID->"83c1dc54-6f75-405b-9d6a-424cc1a3c378"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It was widely held that quantum entanglement is crucial for achieving \
quantum speedups beyond classical computing or precision measurements \
surpassing the quantum standard limit. However, the semiclassical \
implementation of the quantum Fourier transform (Griffiths & Niu, 1996) \
challenged this notion. In the semiclassical scheme, as elaborated upon \
below, single-qubit measurements and subsequent single-qubit gates controlled \
by the measurement outcomes (classical signals) are sufficient to efficiently \
perform the quantum Fourier transform. This semiclassical implementation \
holds significant interest not only from a physical standpoint but also \
considering the current technological capabilities. Notably, since it does \
not necessitate entanglement, a quantum information resource that is \
inherently fragile and challenging to maintain, numerous experiments employ \
this implementation whenever the quantum Fourier transform and/or ",
 ButtonBox["quantum phase estimation",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumPhaseEstimation"],
 " is required (Chiaverini, 2005; Higgins et al., 2007)."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->838521981,ExpressionUUID->"9dbd8cea-d9d8-4fcd-8690-af00b4c12433"],

Cell["\<\
\tThe line of argument in the original work (Griffiths & Niu, 1996) to derive \
the semiclassical implementation of the quantum Fourier transformation is \
interesting in its own right, and it offers another physically-motivated \
derivation of the quantum Fourier transform algorithm. Nevertheless, here, we \
simply make use of the relation between the quantum Fourier transform and its \
inverse.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1191143923,ExpressionUUID->"17fefd1f-18ce-4634-a1f9-f021bc44f0ae"],

Cell["\tThe inverse quantum Fourier transform is given by", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->713356527,ExpressionUUID->"bf5ebef2-6056-4a27-87d5-ad19114142c6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["U", "QFT", "\[Dagger]"], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox["X", "y"]},
      "Ket"]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", 
      SuperscriptBox["2", 
       RowBox[{"n", "/", "2"}]]], 
     RowBox[{
      UnderscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", "x"], 
      RowBox[{
       TemplateBox[{
         SubscriptBox["X", "x"]},
        "Ket"], 
       SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"-", "\[ImaginaryI]"}], "\[VeryThinSpace]", "x", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
         SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}]]}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bf77f3e8-7420-4249-9abe-ab48238df704"],
 ","
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->2129431735,ExpressionUUID->"b9ab8ec3-5575-4818-9ed7-4df0a0f03b6e"],

Cell["which follows directly from the orthogonality relation", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1544192890,ExpressionUUID->"16569c07-a3e2-458f-a956-a01ace3277a7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", 
      SuperscriptBox["2", "n"]], 
     RowBox[{
      UnderscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", "y"], 
      SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", "(", 
         RowBox[{"x", "-", 
          SuperscriptBox["x", "\[Prime]"]}], ")"}], 
        SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}]]}]}], "=", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Delta]", 
     RowBox[{"x", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
      SuperscriptBox["x", "\[Prime]"]}]]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5e11fc09-5d4e-48da-9b80-31ad0ff3e2e5"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->910028235,ExpressionUUID->"310db869-2ae8-4e48-a300-d0b0c4081076"],

Cell["\<\
This expression for the inverse quantum Fourier transform suggests that the \
inverse quantum Fourier transform is just another form of the quantum Fourier \
transform, and indeed, this is a characteristic property common to any kind \
of Fourier transform. This implies that one can recover the original quantum \
Fourier transform from the inverse quantum Fourier transform, and vice versa, \
in several ways.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->466011711,ExpressionUUID->"5576c5a5-30cf-46d8-bfdf-a505489223a8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tFor example, note that  ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["U", "QFT", "\[Dagger]"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox["X", "y"]},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "65fc531e-b919-4629-9fb7-6f8c057d3638"],
 " is an element of the conjugate basis because "
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->385966168,ExpressionUUID->"6b0235ef-5654-4944-8c79-c591e8e70f58"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", "\[ImaginaryI]"}], " ", "x", " ", 
      SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}]], "=", 
    SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
     RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", " ", "x", " ", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]"}], "-", 
        SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}], ")"}]}]]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"9fcc6e59-02b3-4c3d-b546-73fab2784559"],
 " "
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1008799391,ExpressionUUID->"dc4554de-1c39-46a3-8e1b-6009135fff82"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "for any ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["x", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8e4d6337-9d0d-42be-a7ee-626566f73f46"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["y", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5d284879-533f-4f5e-959f-706a6e36dda1"],
 ". In fact, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["U", "QFT", "\[Dagger]"], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox["X", "y"]},
      "Ket"]}], "=", 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox["P", 
       RowBox[{
         SuperscriptBox["2", "n"], "-", "y"}]]},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7f1087d2-1d00-4433-9717-eb68789a0d03"],
 ". More useful in the context of the semiclassical implementation of the \
quantum Fourier transform is to note that the inverse quantum Fourier \
transform ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["U", "QFT", "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7fff2429-8f56-47d8-a57e-89ea70334e82"],
 " is nothing but the quantum Fourier transform with the phase factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
    RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", " ", "x", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "82238196-a65c-491c-9958-816b5bb928d5"],
 " replaced by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["\[ExponentialE]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"-", "\[ImaginaryI]"}], " ", "x", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["p", "y"]}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4833c86f-cbdf-4f58-825e-56a42b7baac6"],
 ". It corresponds to replacing the relative phase shifts ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["Z", "k"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "3df7f145-96ea-4cae-ade5-be0234f92852"],
 " in Figure 4 by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["Z", "k", "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "450ed4ca-76fa-487c-abee-6b7d4932c170"],
 ". Conversely, if we start with the quantum circuit in Figure 4, take its \
Hermitian conjugate (i.e., inverse), and replace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["Z", "k", "\[Dagger]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dc479ca1-70c3-4b4e-8094-4bd2c3c83d9b"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["Z", "k"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d8b398eb-fed2-44bf-a674-5475119fe480"],
 ", then we should recover the original quantum Fourier transform. Through \
this procedure, we get the quantum circuit in Figure 5 for the quantum \
Fourier transform."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->245060466,ExpressionUUID->"4d3e1ee0-2f60-4c54-91fc-20bcf256a73a"],

